=> Modular Arithmetic

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-> Understanding Modular Congruences

a and b are said to be congruent to each other under modulo N, if they leave same remainder
when divided by N

 a ≡ b(mod N)
 13 ≡ 41 (mod 7)

 13 mod 7 = 6
 41 mod 7 = 6

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 13 ≡ 41 (mod 7)                        (13 + 35 + 5)%7 = (53)%7 = 4
                                        (41 + 35 + 5)%7 = (81)%7 = 4

                                        (13*4)%7 = (52)%7 = 3
                                        (41*4)%7 = (164)%7 = 3

                                        (13 + 35 + 5)%7 = (53)%7 = 4
                                        (6 + 0 + 5)%7   = (11)%7 = 4

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
if                                                              a = N*k1 + R
     a ≡ b(mod N)                                               b = N*k2 + R
then
     a-b ≡ 0 (mod N)                                            a-b = N*k1 + R - N*k2 - R
     a-b is divisble by N                                       a-b = N(k1-k2)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
13 ≡ 41 (mod 7)                                                 a-b = N*k
                                                                or
13 - 41 = -28                                                 =>a = N*k +b
41 - 13 = 28                                                    
                                                                13 = 7*(-4) + 41
                                                                41 = 7*(4)  + 13

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-> Multiplication under modulo

if                                                                  13 ≡ 3 (mod 5) and 9 ≡ 4 (mod 5)
     a*b = c                                                        13*9 = 117
then
     a(mod N) * b(mod N) ≡ c (mod N)                                (13%5)*(9%5) ≡ (117 % 5)
     a%N      * b%N      ≡ c (mod N)                                
                                                                    3 * 4 ≡ 2 (mod 5)
res = a*b                                                              12 ≡ 2 (mod 5)
res = ((a%N)*(b%N))%N

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
if                                                                  
     a*b = c                                                        a = N*k1 + r1
then                                                                b = N*k2 + r2
     a(mod N) * b(mod N) ≡ c (mod N)                                c = N*k3 + r3
      r1       *  r2     ≡ r3  

    (N*k1 + r1)*(N*k2 + r2) = (N*k3 + r3)
    N*N*k1*k2 + N*k1*r2 + N*k2*r1 + r1*r2 = N*k3 +r3
    N*N*k1*k2 + N*k1*r2 + N*k2*r1 -N*k3 = N*k3 - (r1*r2)
    N*(N*k1*k2 + k1*r2 + k2*r1 - k3)    = r3 - (r1*r2)

